{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-strategy-tsx","path":"/strategies/storm-surge-barriers/","result":{"data":{"site":{"siteMetadata":{"title":"Changing Coastlines"}},"allFile":{"nodes":[{"absolutePath":"/Users/frank/Projects/active/living-breakwaters-web/content/strategies/storm-surge-barriers/animation/storm-surge-barriers-1.png","relativePath":"storm-surge-barriers/animation/storm-surge-barriers-1.png","childImageSharp":{"fluid":{"src":"/living-breakwaters-web/static/d9817eaf0944dd63346b394f7ee15a0d/ed396/storm-surge-barriers-1.png"}}},{"absolutePath":"/Users/frank/Projects/active/living-breakwaters-web/content/strategies/storm-surge-barriers/animation/storm-surge-barriers-2.png","relativePath":"storm-surge-barriers/animation/storm-surge-barriers-2.png","childImageSharp":{"fluid":{"src":"/living-breakwaters-web/static/6c5d7c0cc0afb97d3aaa44c0137accc0/ed396/storm-surge-barriers-2.png"}}}]},"markdownRemark":{"excerpt":"","html":"<!-- Regular citations -->\n\n      <div class=\"footnotes\">\n        <hr/>\n        <ol style=\"list-style: none;\">\n    \n    <li class=\"footnote-list-item\" id=\"fn-1\" style=\"display:inline\">\n          <span class=\"footnote-marker-text\" style=\"display: inline\">1.</span>\n        \n      <a href=\"#fnref-1\" class=\"footnote-backref\" style=\"display:undefined;\">\n        ↑\n      </a>\n    <p>  Zhu, Xianli, et al., Technologies for Climate Change Adaptation - Coastal Erosion and Flooding. 2010, pp. 54. <a href=\"https://orbit.dtu.dk/files/5699563/Technologies\">https://orbit.dtu.dk/files/5699563/Technologies</a> for Climate Change Adaptation-Coastal Erosion and Flooding.pdf.</p>\n      </li>\n      <br/> <br/>\n    \n\n    <li class=\"footnote-list-item\" id=\"fn-2\" style=\"display:inline\">\n          <span class=\"footnote-marker-text\" style=\"display: inline\">2.</span>\n        \n      <a href=\"#fnref-2\" class=\"footnote-backref\" style=\"display:undefined;\">\n        ↑\n      </a>\n    <p>  Ibid, 55.</p>\n      </li>\n      <br/> <br/>\n    \n\n    <li class=\"footnote-list-item\" id=\"fn-3\" style=\"display:inline\">\n          <span class=\"footnote-marker-text\" style=\"display: inline\">3.</span>\n        \n      <a href=\"#fnref-3\" class=\"footnote-backref\" style=\"display:undefined;\">\n        ↑\n      </a>\n    <p>  Ibid, 57.</p>\n      </li>\n      <br/> <br/>\n    \n\n    <li class=\"footnote-list-item\" id=\"fn-4\" style=\"display:inline\">\n          <span class=\"footnote-marker-text\" style=\"display: inline\">4.</span>\n        \n      <a href=\"#fnref-4\" class=\"footnote-backref\" style=\"display:undefined;\">\n        ↑\n      </a>\n    <p>  Ibid, 61.</p>\n      </li>\n      <br/> <br/>\n    \n\n    <li class=\"footnote-list-item\" id=\"fn-5\" style=\"display:inline\">\n          <span class=\"footnote-marker-text\" style=\"display: inline\">5.</span>\n        \n      <a href=\"#fnref-5\" class=\"footnote-backref\" style=\"display:undefined;\">\n        ↑\n      </a>\n    <p>  Flooding in London. Greater London Authority, Nov. 2002, pp. 21. <a href=\"https://www.london.gov.uk/sites/default/files/gla_migrate_files_destination/archives/assembly-reports-environment-flooding.pdf\">https://www.london.gov.uk/sites/default/files/gla_migrate_files_destination/archives/assembly-reports-environment-flooding.pdf</a>.</p>\n      </li>\n      <br/> <br/>\n    \n\n    <li class=\"footnote-list-item\" id=\"fn-6\" style=\"display:inline\">\n          <span class=\"footnote-marker-text\" style=\"display: inline\">6.</span>\n        \n      <a href=\"#fnref-6\" class=\"footnote-backref\" style=\"display:undefined;\">\n        ↑\n      </a>\n    <p>  Ibid, 21.</p>\n      </li>\n      <br/> <br/>\n    \n\n    <li class=\"footnote-list-item\" id=\"fn-7\" style=\"display:inline\">\n          <span class=\"footnote-marker-text\" style=\"display: inline\">7.</span>\n        \n      <a href=\"#fnref-7\" class=\"footnote-backref\" style=\"display:undefined;\">\n        ↑\n      </a>\n    <p>  Ibid, 21.</p>\n      </li>\n      <br/> <br/>\n    \n\n    <li class=\"footnote-list-item\" id=\"fn-8\" style=\"display:inline\">\n          <span class=\"footnote-marker-text\" style=\"display: inline\">8.</span>\n        \n      <a href=\"#fnref-8\" class=\"footnote-backref\" style=\"display:undefined;\">\n        ↑\n      </a>\n    <p>  Leys, Vincent, and Daniel Bryce. Adapting to Climate Change in Coastal Communities of the Atlantic Provinces, Canada: Land Use Planning and Engineering and Natural Approaches. Mar. 2016, pp. 63. <a href=\"https://research.fit.edu/media/site-specific/researchfitedu/coast-climate-adaptation-library/canada-amp-arctic/canada---atlantic/Leys--Bryce.--2016.--CC-in-Coastal-Communities-of-the-Atlantic-Provinces,-Land-Use,-Engineering-Natural-Approaches.pdf\">https://research.fit.edu/media/site-specific/researchfitedu/coast-climate-adaptation-library/canada-amp-arctic/canada---atlantic/Leys--Bryce.--2016.--CC-in-Coastal-Communities-of-the-Atlantic-Provinces,-Land-Use,-Engineering-Natural-Approaches.pdf</a>.</p>\n      </li>\n      <br/> <br/>\n    \n\n    <li class=\"footnote-list-item\" id=\"fn-9\" style=\"display:inline\">\n          <span class=\"footnote-marker-text\" style=\"display: inline\">9.</span>\n        \n      <a href=\"#fnref-9\" class=\"footnote-backref\" style=\"display:undefined;\">\n        ↑\n      </a>\n    <p>  Ibid, 63.</p>\n      </li>\n      <br/> <br/>\n    \n\n    <li class=\"footnote-list-item\" id=\"fn-10\" style=\"display:inline\">\n          <span class=\"footnote-marker-text\" style=\"display: inline\">10.</span>\n        \n      <a href=\"#fnref-10\" class=\"footnote-backref\" style=\"display:undefined;\">\n        ↑\n      </a>\n    <p>  Ibid, 63.</p>\n      </li>\n      <br/> <br/>\n    \n\n    <li class=\"footnote-list-item\" id=\"fn-11\" style=\"display:inline\">\n          <span class=\"footnote-marker-text\" style=\"display: inline\">11.</span>\n        \n      <a href=\"#fnref-11\" class=\"footnote-backref\" style=\"display:undefined;\">\n        ↑\n      </a>\n    <p>  Cole, Darrell. “Colwell Announces $5-Million Aboiteau for LaPlanche River: Cumberland News Now.” News, 23 Sept. 2014, <a href=\"https://www.cumberlandnewsnow.com/news/local/colwell-announces-5-million-aboiteau-for-laplanche-river-30277/\">https://www.cumberlandnewsnow.com/news/local/colwell-announces-5-million-aboiteau-for-laplanche-river-30277/</a>.  </p>\n      </li>\n      <br/> <br/>\n    \n\n    <li class=\"footnote-list-item\" id=\"fn-12\" style=\"display:inline\">\n          <span class=\"footnote-marker-text\" style=\"display: inline\">12.</span>\n        \n      <a href=\"#fnref-12\" class=\"footnote-backref\" style=\"display:undefined;\">\n        ↑\n      </a>\n    <p>  Deltares. Enabling Delta Life. Overview storm surge barriers. <a href=\"http://www.masterpiece.dk/UploadetFiles/10852/25/Deltares_2018_Overview_storm_surge_barriers_komprimeret.pdf\">http://www.masterpiece.dk/UploadetFiles/10852/25/Deltares_2018_Overview_storm_surge_barriers_komprimeret.pdf</a></p>\n      </li>\n      <br/> <br/>\n    \n\n    <li class=\"footnote-list-item\" id=\"fn-13\" style=\"display:inline\">\n          <span class=\"footnote-marker-text\" style=\"display: inline\">13.</span>\n        \n      <a href=\"#fnref-13\" class=\"footnote-backref\" style=\"display:undefined;\">\n        ↑\n      </a>\n    <p>  Esteban et al. (2019). Handbook of Coastal Disaster Mitigation for Engineers and Planners 2015, Pages 723-747. Chapter 33 - Adaptation to Sea Level Rise in Tokyo Bay: Opportunities for a Storm Surge Barrier? <a href=\"https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/engineering/storm-surge-barrier\">https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/engineering/storm-surge-barrier</a></p>\n      </li>\n      <br/> <br/>\n    \n\n    <li class=\"footnote-list-item\" id=\"fn-14\" style=\"display:inline\">\n          <span class=\"footnote-marker-text\" style=\"display: inline\">14.</span>\n        \n      <a href=\"#fnref-14\" class=\"footnote-backref\" style=\"display:undefined;\">\n        ↑\n      </a>\n    <p>  Climate Technology Center and Network. (nd). Storm surge barriers and closure dams<a href=\"https://www.ctc-n.org/technologies/storm-surge-barriers-and-closure-dams\">https://www.ctc-n.org/technologies/storm-surge-barriers-and-closure-dams</a></p>\n      </li>\n      <br/> <br/>\n    \n<!-- Images -->\n\n    <li class=\"footnote-list-item\" id=\"fn-i1\" style=\"display:inline\">\n          <span class=\"footnote-marker-text\" style=\"display: inline\">i1.</span>\n        \n      <a href=\"#fnref-i1\" class=\"footnote-backref\" style=\"display:undefined;\">\n        ↑\n      </a>\n    <p>  Roberts, Andy. Thames Barrier. <a href=\"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/49/Thames_Barrier_03.jpg/1280px-Thames_Barrier_03.jpg\">https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/49/Thames_Barrier_03.jpg/1280px-Thames_Barrier_03.jpg</a>.</p>\n      </li>\n      <br/> <br/>\n    \n\n    <li class=\"footnote-list-item\" id=\"fn-i2\" style=\"display:inline\">\n          <span class=\"footnote-marker-text\" style=\"display: inline\">i2.</span>\n        \n      <a href=\"#fnref-i2\" class=\"footnote-backref\" style=\"display:undefined;\">\n        ↑\n      </a>\n    <p>  Figure 1. Netherlands News. (2018). Storm Eleanor: Dutch national water authority closed all five big storm surge barriers. <a href=\"https://www.dutchwatersector.com/news/storm-eleanor-dutch-national-water-authority-closed-all-five-big-storm-surge-barriers\">https://www.dutchwatersector.com/news/storm-eleanor-dutch-national-water-authority-closed-all-five-big-storm-surge-barriers</a></p>\n      </li>\n      <br/> <br/>\n    \n\n    <li class=\"footnote-list-item\" id=\"fn-i3\" style=\"display:inline\">\n          <span class=\"footnote-marker-text\" style=\"display: inline\">i3.</span>\n        \n      <a href=\"#fnref-i3\" class=\"footnote-backref\" style=\"display:undefined;\">\n        ↑\n      </a>\n    <p>  Figure 2. Science Hudson.org. (2020). Hudson River Storm Surge Barriers <a href=\"https://www.scenichudson.org/our-work/advocacy/storm-surge-barriers/\">https://www.scenichudson.org/our-work/advocacy/storm-surge-barriers/</a></p>\n      </li>\n      <br/> <br/>\n    \n\n    <li class=\"footnote-list-item\" id=\"fn-i4\" style=\"display:inline\">\n          <span class=\"footnote-marker-text\" style=\"display: inline\">i4.</span>\n        \n      <a href=\"#fnref-i4\" class=\"footnote-backref\" style=\"display:undefined;\">\n        ↑\n      </a>\n    <p>  Figure 3. BBC New. 2007. New Thames barrier could be built <a href=\"http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/6964281.stm\">http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/6964281.stm</a></p>\n      </li>\n      \n    </ol></div>","id":"35be0a4c-5325-585d-a143-1433d7cbd5b5","frontmatter":{"date":"October 23, 2020","strategyTypes":"Protect","title":"Storm Surge Barriers"}},"allMarkdownRemark":{"edges":[{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/amphibious-buildings/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Accommodate","title":"Amphibious Buildings"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/barrier-islands/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Protect","title":"Barrier Islands"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/beach-nourishment/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Protect","title":"Beach Nourishment"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/breakwaters/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Protect","title":"Breakwaters"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/coastal-wetlands/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Protect","title":"Coastal Wetlands"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/development-permits/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Retreat","title":"Development Permits"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/development-transfers/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Retreat","title":"Development Transfers"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/dikes/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Protect","title":"Dikes"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/dry-floodproofing/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Accommodate","title":"Dry Floodproofing"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/dune-building-restoration/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Protect","title":"Dune Building / Restoration"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/easement-and-covenants/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Avoid","title":"Easement and Covenants"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/emergency-planning-and-preparedness/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Accommodate","title":"Emergency Planning Preparedness"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/evacuation-routes/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Accommodate","title":"Evacuation Routes"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/floodwalls/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Protect","title":"Floodwalls"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/foreshore-tenure/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Retreat","title":"Foreshore Tenure"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/groynes/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Protect","title":"Groynes"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/land-acquisition/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Avoid","title":"Land Acquisition"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/land-trust/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Avoid","title":"Land Trust"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/protected-area-zoning/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Avoid","title":"Protected Area Zoning"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/reef-systems/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Protect","title":"Reef Systems"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/scour-protection/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Protect","title":"Scour Protection"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/seawall/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Protect","title":"Seawall"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/secondary-dikes/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Accommodate","title":"Secondary Dikes"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/storm-surge-barriers/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Protect","title":"Storm Surge Barriers"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/subdivision-regulation-and-development-control/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Retreat","title":"Subdivision Regulation and Development Control"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/warning-system/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Accommodate","title":"Warning System"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/wet-floodproofing/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Accommodate","title":"Wet Floodproofing"}}}]}},"pageContext":{"animationSlug":"//strategies/storm-surge-barriers/animation.*png/","slug":"/strategies/storm-surge-barriers/","foo":"bar","subpages":{"challenges":"<ul>\n<li>High construction and maintenance cost </li>\n<li>Affects nearby environments and transfers risk onto nearby properties and communities</li>\n<li>May negatively affect water quality in the bay area </li>\n<li>Mostly suitable for locations where inlets and narrow river mouths can be closed <sup id=\"fnref-13\"><a href=\"#fn-13\" class=\"footnote-ref\">13</a></sup> <sup id=\"fnref-14\"><a href=\"#fn-14\" class=\"footnote-ref\">14</a></sup></li>\n</ul>","benefits":"<ul>\n<li>Protects tidal inlets and estuaries from extreme wave events</li>\n<li>Reduces cost and maintenance of coastal flood defenses on the landward side</li>\n<li>Protects an entire bay area including ports. </li>\n<li>Can be utilized as a bridge or railroad link</li>\n<li>Provides infrastructure support for the development of derelict areas. </li>\n</ul>","examples":["<h3>La Planche River Aboiteau</h3>\n<h4>Amherst NS, Canada</h4>\n<p>In 2015, the province of Nova Scotia awarded $5 million in the replacement of the old aboiteau on the La Planche River.<sup id=\"fnref-8\"><a href=\"#fn-8\" class=\"footnote-ref\">8</a></sup> An aboiteau is a one-way storm barrier that controls the flow of water through a dike.<sup id=\"fnref-9\"><a href=\"#fn-9\" class=\"footnote-ref\">9</a></sup> It is typically used to protect valuable assets such as marshland and agricultural land by reducing the amount of flooding during high tides or storm surges. The design and location of the new aboiteau were intended to reduce the maintenance of existing dikes and to increase the crest elevation to accommodate a rise in sea level.<sup id=\"fnref-10\"><a href=\"#fn-10\" class=\"footnote-ref\">10</a></sup> The new aboiteau is part of the 241 km of dikes and 260 aboiteau that are operated by the Agriculture Department, under the Marshlands Conservation Act. The act is intended to protect over 43,000 acres of Nova Scotia marshlands.<sup id=\"fnref-11\"><a href=\"#fn-11\" class=\"footnote-ref\">11</a></sup></p>","<h3>Thames Barrier</h3>\n<h4>London ENG, UK</h4>\n<p>The Thames Barrier is one of the largest movable storm surge barriers in the world. It was constructed in response to the frequent tidal surges that London experienced before the Flood Protection Act of 1972.<sup id=\"fnref-5\"><a href=\"#fn-5\" class=\"footnote-ref\">5</a></sup> Construction began in 1974 and the finished structure was put into operation in 1982.<sup id=\"fnref-6\"><a href=\"#fn-6\" class=\"footnote-ref\">6</a></sup> According to the Environment Agency, the Thames Barrier cost around £535 million to construct. The Thames Barrier is built to provide a high level of protection for several decades. In 2000-2001 there was an unusual number of closures. Then, it was projected that the trend will continue because of climate change and sea-level rise.<sup id=\"fnref-7\"><a href=\"#fn-7\" class=\"footnote-ref\">7</a></sup></p>"],"images":["<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 481px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/living-breakwaters-web/static/efec03aaa67b139d47e97d60981f5d22/d024a/Figure1.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 52.02702702702703%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"image\"\n        title=\"image\"\n        src=\"/living-breakwaters-web/static/efec03aaa67b139d47e97d60981f5d22/d024a/Figure1.png\"\n        srcset=\"/living-breakwaters-web/static/efec03aaa67b139d47e97d60981f5d22/12f09/Figure1.png 148w,\n/living-breakwaters-web/static/efec03aaa67b139d47e97d60981f5d22/e4a3f/Figure1.png 295w,\n/living-breakwaters-web/static/efec03aaa67b139d47e97d60981f5d22/d024a/Figure1.png 481w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 481px) 100vw, 481px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>\nMaeslant barrier, Netherlands <sup id=\"fnref-2\"><a href=\"#fn-2\" class=\"footnote-ref\">2</a></sup></p>","<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 318px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/living-breakwaters-web/static/129b64669ed394e2db4eb34b65d105ee/cd2d9/Figure3.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 75%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"image\"\n        title=\"image\"\n        src=\"/living-breakwaters-web/static/129b64669ed394e2db4eb34b65d105ee/cd2d9/Figure3.png\"\n        srcset=\"/living-breakwaters-web/static/129b64669ed394e2db4eb34b65d105ee/12f09/Figure3.png 148w,\n/living-breakwaters-web/static/129b64669ed394e2db4eb34b65d105ee/e4a3f/Figure3.png 295w,\n/living-breakwaters-web/static/129b64669ed394e2db4eb34b65d105ee/cd2d9/Figure3.png 318w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 318px) 100vw, 318px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>\nThames river barrier UK <sup id=\"fnref-4\"><a href=\"#fn-4\" class=\"footnote-ref\">4</a></sup></p>","<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 370px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/living-breakwaters-web/static/a0732cd534e3fc1ba1f1f4867b02fff2/1efb2/Figure2.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 68.91891891891892%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"image\"\n        title=\"image\"\n        src=\"/living-breakwaters-web/static/a0732cd534e3fc1ba1f1f4867b02fff2/1efb2/Figure2.png\"\n        srcset=\"/living-breakwaters-web/static/a0732cd534e3fc1ba1f1f4867b02fff2/12f09/Figure2.png 148w,\n/living-breakwaters-web/static/a0732cd534e3fc1ba1f1f4867b02fff2/e4a3f/Figure2.png 295w,\n/living-breakwaters-web/static/a0732cd534e3fc1ba1f1f4867b02fff2/1efb2/Figure2.png 370w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 370px) 100vw, 370px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>\nHudson River Storm Surge Barriers <sup id=\"fnref-3\"><a href=\"#fn-3\" class=\"footnote-ref\">3</a></sup></p>"],"types":"<ul>\n<li><strong>Sector gates</strong> are radial structures comprising two gates with lateral support. Both the gates and arms create a section of a circle that turns around a vertical axis. The gates move based on the water pressure exerted against them. </li>\n<li><strong>Mitre gates</strong> are flat gates that are comprised of two units. When the two units are closed, they lean against each other forming a wedge in the direction where the water level is highest. </li>\n<li><strong>Swinging gates or barge gates</strong> are flat and rotate around a vertical axis at one side of a waterway. Swinging gates are designed to prevent tidal intrusions only in low water flow. </li>\n<li><strong>Rotary segment gates</strong> are cylindrical segments that rotate around a horizontal axis. When a rotary gate is open, the barrier rests on a sill made from concrete that is embedded in the waterway. <sup id=\"fnref-12\"><a href=\"#fn-12\" class=\"footnote-ref\">12</a></sup> </li>\n</ul>","summary":"<p>Storm surge barriers are heavily engineered movable or fixed barriers/gates that are closed to prevent flooding during bad weather forecasts.<sup id=\"fnref-1\"><a href=\"#fn-1\" class=\"footnote-ref\">1</a></sup> They are commonly located across the mouth of a tidal inlet or estuaries to control the water level and prevent excessive amounts of  water from entering the estuary.<sup id=\"fnref-2\"><a href=\"#fn-2\" class=\"footnote-ref\">2</a></sup> Storm surge barriers can be very beneficial for secondary flood protection,  on the landward side of the barrier. For example, storm surge barriers can reduce the maintenance and construction cost of secondary storm protection structures.<sup id=\"fnref-3\"><a href=\"#fn-3\" class=\"footnote-ref\">3</a></sup> Because these barriers require a high level of engineering feasibility studies and because they incur high construction costs, they can be challenging to implement as a cost-effective adaptation strategy. Additionally, storm surge barriers are more appropriate in areas with tidal lets that can be closed.<sup id=\"fnref-4\"><a href=\"#fn-4\" class=\"footnote-ref\">4</a></sup> </p>"},"previous":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/wet-floodproofing/image1/"},"html":"<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 464px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/living-breakwaters-web/static/feaf38cc90af8c000de4be14bbea4958/69096/Figure1.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 57.432432432432435%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"image\"\n        title=\"image\"\n        src=\"/living-breakwaters-web/static/feaf38cc90af8c000de4be14bbea4958/69096/Figure1.png\"\n        srcset=\"/living-breakwaters-web/static/feaf38cc90af8c000de4be14bbea4958/12f09/Figure1.png 148w,\n/living-breakwaters-web/static/feaf38cc90af8c000de4be14bbea4958/e4a3f/Figure1.png 295w,\n/living-breakwaters-web/static/feaf38cc90af8c000de4be14bbea4958/69096/Figure1.png 464w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 464px) 100vw, 464px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>\nWet floodproofing for a walkout basement <sup id=\"fnref-1\"><a href=\"#fn-1\" class=\"footnote-ref\">1</a></sup></p>","frontmatter":{"title":""}},"next":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/wet-floodproofing/example2/"},"html":"<h3>Spray-and-wash Basement</h3>\n<h4>Calgary AB, Canada</h4>\n<p>In Calgary, homeowners renovate their basements with flood-resistant materials. The renovation required the existing basement to be gutted and replaced with materials such as steel stairs, polished concrete floors, and walls that are impervious to water.<sup id=\"fnref-7\"><a href=\"#fn-7\" class=\"footnote-ref\">7</a></sup> The renovation materials cost about 30 percent more than the conventional building materials.<sup id=\"fnref-8\"><a href=\"#fn-8\" class=\"footnote-ref\">8</a></sup> The use of water-resistant material allows for post-flood cleanup to be much faster and less costly.</p>","frontmatter":{"title":""}}}},"staticQueryHashes":["3000541721"]}